es. Each cantata is discussed individually, but there is also a broader consideration of aspects concerning them collectively, such as performance practice, topical allusion, and the conventions of Italian verse. The author argues that while Vivalid's cantatas are not as innovative as his concertos and operas, he produced several masterpieces in the genre that rank with his best music. MICHAEL TALBOT is Emeritus Professor of Music at the University of Liverpool.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aSolo cantatas, SecularzItalyxHistory and criticism. 4aMusic. 7aMUSIC / History & Criticism.2bisacsh  aItalian verse.  aVivaldi's chamber cantatas.  acomposer's biography.  aconfessional culture.  aliterary and musical background.  aperformance practice.  atopical allusion.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978184615454640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781846154546423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781846154546/original  a978-3-11-143139-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles